Chalco, Cheung Kong, Link REIT: Hong Kong Equities Preview

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-09-22T00:54:35Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-22/chalco-cheung-kong-link-reit-hong-kong-equities-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  dropped 1 percent to 18,824.17. The
Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H
shares of Chinese companies, fell 0.9 percent to 9,822.67.  Developers: Hong Kong’s housing market had shown “signs of
weakening” on government measures to curb property prices and
signs global economic growth is slowing, the Hong Kong Monetary
Authority said in its half-yearly report yesterday.  Home prices 
in the city have risen more than 70 percent since early 2009 on
low  mortgage rates , the lack of new housing supply and an influx
of buyers from other parts of China.  Sun Hung Kai Properties Ltd. (16)  (16 HK), the world’s biggest
developer by market value, fell 0.6 percent to HK$101.20.  Cheung
Kong Holdings Ltd. (1)  (1 HK), the real-estate company controlled by
billionaire  Li Ka-shing , dropped 2 percent to HK$94.  Hang Lung
Properties Ltd. (101)  (101 HK), Hong Kong’s third-largest homebuilder
by market value, slid 2 percent to HK$24.45.  Aluminum Corp. of China Ltd. (2600 HK): Plans by China’s
biggest producer of the metal to sell as many as 1 billion A-
shares through private placement has been approved by the China
Securities Regulatory Commission. Chalco, as the company is
known, slid 1.7 percent to HK$4.14.  Link Real Estate Investment Trust (823 HK): The Hong Kong-
based shopping-mall operator was rated “buy” in new coverage
at Deutsche Bank AG. The brokerage set a share-price forecast of
HK$30.43 and said it expects strong upside potential for the
company’s rental income. The stock gained 0.9 percent to
HK$26.95.  Hong Kong  Exchanges & Clearing Ltd. (388 HK): The Hong Kong
bourse operator said it appointed Richard Leung, currently chief
technology officer of Chi-X Global Inc., as co-head of its
information technology division and senior vice president. Leung
will co-head the division with Bill Chow. The stock retreated
2.6 percent to HK$133.20.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan Burgos in Singapore at 
 jburgos4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle in Tokyo at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 